# Vitess Grafana Dashboard

The Vitess project provides official Grafana dashboards for monitoring Vitess clusters.
There are two ways to import them into the EuroScale Grafana instance:

## Option 1: Import from grafana.com (Dashboard ID 11111)

1. Open Grafana at the LoadBalancer IP printed by `deploy.sh`
2. Log in with the admin credentials
3. Hover over **+** (Create) in the sidebar → **Import**
4. Enter dashboard ID: **11111**
5. Select the Prometheus data source (named `Prometheus` or `kube-prometheus-stack-prometheus`)
6. Click **Import**

> **Note:** Grafana.com dashboard ID 11111 is the community-maintained Vitess dashboard.
> If ID 11111 is unavailable, use Option 2 below.

## Option 2: Use Vitess Example Dashboards (recommended)

Grab the official Vitess example dashboards from the [Vitess repository](https://github.com/vitessio/vitess/tree/main/examples/operator):

```bash
# Fetch the dashboard JSONs from the Vitess repo
curl -L https://raw.githubusercontent.com/vitessio/vitess/main/examples/operator/dashboards/vitess-cluster-overview.json \
  -o /tmp/vitess-cluster-overview.json

curl -L https://raw.githubusercontent.com/vitessio/vitess/main/examples/operator/dashboards/vitess-vttablet.json \
  -o /tmp/vitess-vttablet.json
```

Then import:
1. Grafana → **Dashboards** → **Import**
2. Click **Upload JSON file**
3. Select each downloaded JSON file
4. Link to the Prometheus data source

## Pre-configured Dashboards (kube-prometheus-stack)

The kube-prometheus-stack Helm chart ships with these dashboards out of the box:

| Dashboard | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| Nodes | Cluster node metrics (CPU, mem, disk, network) |
| Pods | Pod-level resource usage |
| Kubernetes / Compute Resources | Namespace/workload resource breakdown |
| Kubernetes / Networking | Network I/O per pod/namespace |
| Prometheus | Prometheus self-monitoring |
| etcd | etcd cluster health (if using etcd backend) |

## Metric Sources (via ServiceMonitors)

After `deploy.sh` applies the Vitess metrics config, the following Vitess components
will be scraped by Prometheus automatically:

- **vtgate** — Query routing metrics (queries/sec, errors, latency)
- **vttablet** — Tablet-level metrics (replication lag, QPS, row counts)
- **vtctld** — Topology / cluster management metrics
- **vtbackup** — Backup job metrics

Verify targets are up:
```bash
kubectl port-forward -n monitoring svc/kube-prometheus-stack-prometheus 9090:9090
# Open http://localhost:9090/targets
```
